Description.div: On the following pages you will be asked %System_NumberOfQuestions% questions about environmental offences under the RMA.

You may be asked three different types of questions: multiple choice, true/false or yes/no. Answer each question by clicking the button to the left of the most appropriate response.
After you answer the last question, you will be given the chance to review and then submit your answers.
Please note that if you Exit the quiz before clicking the Submit Answers button then your answers will not be saved.
To move between questions, use the ◄ and ► navigation buttons on the bottom right of the page.

div.strong: WG Limited runs a waste treatment plant. The plant contains a large tank to hold the waste material, which is dug into the ground. Soon after the new plant opens, there is a malfunction, the tank overflows and a large amount of waste is discharged into a nearby stream causing pollution. The cause of the overflow is a blockage in the outflow pipe, which WG was not aware of. Is WG Limited liable for prosecution under the RMA?

Answer.Description: No, WGL is not liable because it did not intend to cause the discharge of the waste.
Yes, the blockage was a foreseeable event and as long as there is a link between WGL and the discharge, they will be liable.
No, the blockage had not happened before, so WGL cannot be legally responsible.
An order from the Court requiring the land owner to stop carrying out an activity that is causing adverse environmental effects.
A notice issued by the council to prevent activities which breach a rule in a district plan, a condition in a resource consent, or a provision of the RMA.

div.strong: How long have you got to challenge an abatement notice if you are not prepared to comply with it?

Answer.Description: Three months from date of receipt.
Fifteen working days from date of receipt.

div.strong: RM Limited operates an oil processing plant. During a heavy storm an employee of RML opens a valve in one of the processing tanks to avoid the risk of the tank overflowing. The valve is opened too widely and oil is discharged via the stormwater drains into a nearby stream. Is it a defence for RML and its employee to say that the storm was something beyond their control?

Answer.Description: Yes, RML cannot be held responsible for natural events such as storm rainfall.
No, a storm is a normal natural event and RML should have taken appropriate preventive measures to avoid the tank overflowing.

div.strong: What is the maximum penalty under the RMA?

Answer.Description: A fine of up to $1,000,000.
Community Service of up to 200 hours.
Up to two years in prison or a fine of up to $300,000 for an individual and up to $600,000 for a company.

div.strong: Mr Johnston buys a factory on a large area of land. Unknown to him, the previous owner dumped a number of drums of a hazardous waste at the back of that land. The council becomes aware of this via Mr Johnson’s neighbour, Repcorp, who are concerned about possible contamination of their own land which could affect their market garden business. What remedy is available to Repcorp?

Answer.Description: Repcorp can take no enforcement action directly. They should speak to the council about the problem and persuade them to take action.
Repcorp can apply to the Court for an enforcement order to require a clean up.

div.strong: GR Limited are building a new factory. They think they have all the necessary consents to undertake this, but during a council inspection it is discovered they have failed to obtain an appropriate earthworks consent (for foundation construction). Council serve GRL with an abatement notice to stop works until the necessary consent is obtained. GRL’s planner disagrees with the council’s interpretation of the district plan rules and GRL therefore appeals council’s decision. Does GRL need to comply with the abatement notice (i.e. stop work) while they are waiting for the appeal to be determined?

Answer.Description: No, they can continue with construction during this time.
Yes, the notice must be complied with even if an appeal has been lodged. The Court can be asked to stay the notice separately, i.e. to prevent it taking effect prior to the appeal being heard.

div.strong: AB Limited operates a sewerage treatment facility. A valve fails to close properly on a pipe which fills a storage tank. Sewerage overflows from the tank and flows into the nearby river, causing much pollution. Which statement is correct?

Answer.Description: ABL did not cause the pollution because it did not know that the valve was faulty.
The employee who last installed the valve caused the pollution, not ABL.

ABL caused the pollution because it was in control of the operation which led to the pollution. ABL should have procedures in place to ensure the valves are not faulty and have facilities in place to contain spills in case events like this happen.

div.strong: Environmental offences are mostly criminal offences. True or false?

Answer.Description: True
False

div.strong: You can commit an environmental offence even if you did not intend to cause damage to the environment. True or false?

Answer.Description: True
False

div.strong: Choose the correct answer. To minimise the chance of being held liable for offences committed by a contractor, an organisation should:

Answer.Description: Always choose the contractor with the lowest quote.
Always choose the contractor who can do the job the fastest.
Only choose experienced, qualified, and competent contractors.
Infringement notices can only be issued with the approval of the Environment Court.
Infringement notices are the most serious tool under the RMA for dealing with environmental offences.
Infringement notices involve instant fines, and are issued by Council Officers. They are used for low level offences under the RMA.

Description.strong: Offences under the RMA are ‘strict liability’ – this means that:

Answer.Description: Offence provisions under the RMA are interpreted strictly, i.e. an accused person will get the benefit of the doubt.
There is no need to prove that a person intended to commit an offence, he or she will be liable regardless.
A person who breaches the Act will always be liable – there are no defences of any kind.
